## Summary
There are multiple test failures in both backend and frontend test suites that pre-date the SPX market data service implementation (PR #41). These need to be addressed to restore test suite integrity.

Located primarily in:
- `api/test_ai_assessment.py` - 38 failures related to AI assessment service
- `api/test_ib_connection.py` - 6 failures (API returning bool instead of dict)
- `api/test_ib_options_chain.py` - 3 failures (database mocking issues)

### Key Issues:
1. **AI Assessment Service**: Tests expecting `assessment_service` but getting `None` or wrong types
2. **IB Connection API**: Endpoint returning boolean `True` instead of expected dictionary format
3. **Database Mocking**: Tests using in-memory SQLite but hitting foreign key/table issues

## Frontend Test Failures
Multiple Playwright E2E tests failing due to:
- Missing mock data endpoints
- Component visibility issues
- Timing/race conditions

## Context
These failures were discovered during PR #41 review but are unrelated to the SPX market data service implementation. They appear to be from previous development work that wasn't fully tested.

## Recommended Approach
1. Fix AI assessment service initialization and mocking
2. Correct IB connection API response format
3. Update database test fixtures for proper table creation
4. Add missing mock endpoints for E2E tests
5. Ensure all tests pass before future PRs

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] All backend tests pass (currently 71/118)
- [ ] All frontend Vitest tests pass
- [ ] All Playwright E2E tests pass
- [ ] CI/CD pipeline shows green

Related to work completed in PR #41 (SPX market data service) but not caused by it.

issue.title: Add support for active `CentOS Stream` repositories
issue.body:
## Summary
Add `CentOS Stream` repository support to `mdapi/metasource` to expand metadata coverage beyond current Fedora repositories.

## Background
Following the epic outlined in issue #369 by @james-antill, point 8 specifically calls for "Adding the active CentOS stream repos".

## Technical Requirements

### Configuration Layer Changes

- Extend repository configuration in `metasource/config/base.go`:
  - Add `CentOS Stream` URLs to `LINKDICT` and `REPODICT` maps
  - Add `CentOS` base URL constants (e.g., `CENTOSSERVER`: "https://mirror.stream.centos.org/")
  - Support CentOS Stream repository patterns

### Repository Discovery & Population

- Multi-distribution branch detection in `metasource/driver/popu.go`:
  - Replace Fedora-specific Bodhi API dependency with configurable branch sources
  - Implement `CentOS Stream` version discovery mechanism
  - Support `CentOS Stream` naming conventions (stream-8, stream-9, etc.)

### Metadata Processing Pipeline

- Repository metadata handling:
  - Ensure compatibility with `CentOS Stream` `repomd.xml` structure
  - Handle potential differences in metadata compression formats
  - Validate `CentOS Stream` repository priorities

I would like to give this one a try.

issue.title: 1080p MP4 download often falls back to 640x360
issue.body:
When selecting 1080p video quality and MP4 format, the download does not always retrieve the requested resolution. Most of the time, it pulls a 640x360 video instead.

To get the correct 1080p file, I have to delete the lower-resolution version and retry the download ‚Äî sometimes up to 5 attempts before it finally grabs the 1080p version.

Environment:

* Running latest Docker image (2025.07.31)

* macOS host

Steps to reproduce:

1. Select a video that has 1080p available.

2. Choose 1080p quality and MP4 format.

3. Start download.

4. Check the file resolution ‚Äî often it‚Äôs 640x360.

5. Repeat download until 1080p is eventually fetched.

Expected behavior:
When selecting 1080p MP4, the first download should consistently retrieve the 1080p version.

Actual behavior:
Downloads often fall back to 640x360 resolution, requiring multiple retries.

While it is one of the largest major releases of Jest ever, we admit that three years for a major release is too long. In the future, we are aiming to make more frequent major releases to keep Jest great for the next decade.

If you want to skip all the news and just get going, run npm install jest@^30.0.0 and follow the migration guide: Upgrading from Jest 29 to 30.

  • [babel-jest] Add option excludeJestPreset to allow opting out of babel-preset-jest (#15164)
  • [expect] Revert #15038 to fix expect(fn).toHaveBeenCalledWith(expect.objectContaining(...)) when there are multiple calls (#15508)
  • [jest-circus, jest-cli, jest-config] Add waitNextEventLoopTurnForUnhandledRejectionEvents flag to minimise performance impact of correct detection of unhandled promise rejections introduced in #14315 (#14681)
  • [jest-circus] Add a waitBeforeRetry option to jest.retryTimes (#14738)
  • [jest-circus] Add a retryImmediately option to jest.retryTimes (#14696)
  • [jest-circus, jest-jasmine2] Allow setupFilesAfterEnv to export an async function (#10962)

issue.title: Fix issue #382 (multiple publish output files with same relative path)
issue.body:
Fixes #382: On Windows, runtime files from backend packages are currently flattened during copy. This means that all files from subfolders end up in the same output directory, causing conflicts when multiple files share the same name.

## Proposed fix

1. Correct the file [`LLamaSharpBackend.props`](https://github.com/SciSharp/LLamaSharp/blob/master/LLama/runtimes/build/LLamaSharpBackend.props) as shown in the changes included in this PR.

2. When building for Windows, and after installing the Windows-specific backend packages, make sure to add `ExcludeAssets="Native"` to the `PackageReference` in the `.csproj`, as shown below:

```xml
<PackageReference Include="LLamaSharp.Backend.Cpu" Version="0.24.0" ExcludeAssets="Native"/>
```

Although `ExcludeAssets="Native"` is strictly necessary only for Windows backends when building on Windows, it shouldn‚Äôt cause issues for other backends. To be safe, it can be applied to all imported backend packages. I have tested this with both `LLamaSharp.Backend.Cpu` and `LLamaSharp.Backend.Android` installed in the same MAUI project. This attribute tells MSBuild not to copy the runtime files from the NuGet package to the output directory, because copying is already handled correctly in the `LLamaSharpBackend.props` file updated in step 1.

## How to Apply this fix before it is merged

If you urgently need to fix this issue, you can temporarily apply this change by copying the corrected `LLamaSharpBackend.props` content (from step 1) into each backend package directory, e.g.:

```
C:\Users\<your user>\.nuget\packages\<llamasharp backend>\<version>\build\netstandard2.0\<llamasharp backend>.props
```

and then import the package as indicated in step 2. 

**Note:** this modification will be lost if the package is updated.

## Future improvements:
Avoid using the default `Runtimes` folder, since MSBuild always flattens its contents building for windows causing conflicts. Using a custom folder for runtime files would eliminate the need to set `ExcludeAssets="Native"` in the package reference, and then change the `LLamaSharpBackend.props` file to correctly fetch runtime files from the custom folder.

## Tests
I tested this fix on a limited scenario with a MAUI project having both `LLamaSharp.Backend.Cpu` and `LLamaSharp.Backend.Android` installed. The goal was to ensure the app works on both types of devices. Given the large heterogeneity of the backends, I hope this fix will work for other backends as well.

comment.body:
Glad I could help, this issue had been around for a while, let‚Äôs see if the tests confirm the fix.
At the moment, with my fix, the runtimes are packaged into the NuGet packages only under the LLamaSharpRuntimes directory, but then imported into the project under the runtimes folder. This way, nothing should change on the code side and the runtimes end up where they‚Äôre expected to be.

### One note
I‚Äôm not sure why, but the last time I worked on this bug I was able to pack the NuGets with the original paths. This time, however, I had to adjust them. In all the `.nuspec` files the src attribute of the `<file>` elements no longer starts with `runtimes/` but with `../`.

For example:
`<file src="../deps/noavx/ggml.dll" target="LLamaSharpRuntimes\win-x64\native\noavx\ggml.dll" />`

I hope this doesn‚Äôt break the way you build the packages, if it does, please let me know and I‚Äôll restore the src paths to their previous state.

### Testing
As before, I tested with a MAUI project using LLamaSharp.Backend.Cpu and LLamaSharp.Backend.Android. This time, I added the packages using the usual NuGet Package Manager GUI, and it was not necessary to use `ExcludeAssets="Native"`.
